  "prompt": "Is brain transplant true?",
  "response": "As of my last update in October 2023, the concept of a brain transplant remains largely theoretical and has not been successfully conducted in humans or animals. While there have been significant advancements in neuroscience, neurosurgery, and organ transplantation, the complexity of the brain, its connections, and the ethical considerations present formidable challenges.\n\nA brain transplant would involve not just moving the brain but also reconnecting billions of neural connections to the spinal cord, body, and other organs\u2014a task that is currently beyond our scientific and medical capabilities. In addition, the identity and consciousness attached to the brain raise profound ethical and philosophical questions about the nature of self and personhood.\n\nTherefore, while scientists and researchers may explore various aspects related to brain functionality and transplantation in a theoretical or experimental framework, a complete and successful brain transplant is not currently feasible.",
